March 13 at 3:55 PM ·

Beginning Wednesday, March 18, InspireNOLA will provide meals to anyone 18 or below, from any school. InspireNOLA will set up two hubs to serve grab-and-go breakfast and lunches. Meals will be available Monday through Friday, from 9am to 12pm.

The hub locations are:

• Westbank – Alice Harte Charter School – 5300 Berkley Dr. New Orleans, LA 70131
• Eastbank – McDonogh #35 High School – 4000 Cadillac St. New Orleans, LA 70122

Please note: As other locations for meals become available across the city, we will post an updated list on our website and social media.

For more information visit, http://www.inspirenolacharterschools.org/coronavirus.

#InspireNOLA #NOLAEd

shared_text:
InspireNOLA Charter Schools
April 23, 2019 at 2:42 PM ·

“I had a little boy in my class who came from a very hard life. His mother was on drugs and he started off in kindergarten not even knowing a letter from a number. He didn’t know how to spell his name. Didn’t even really know his last name. He started off very low. And, just taking him in and knowing that he needed that love, that extra help.... And, seeing him grow so much. He went from a student that was getting zeros to mastering tests at the end. Just seeing the growth in how much and how far he came, even from a hard life. He was actually so inspiring that I named my little boy after him. He’s one of those kids that I will never forget because the odds were so against him.”
_
Kim Plaisance
Kindergarten Teacher
Alice Harte Charter School

"The Inspired: The Soul of InspireNOLA" is a collection of portraits and stories that showcases #InspireNOLA's greatest asset: our educators.
#TheSoulofInspireNOLA #NOLAEd #NewOrleans

post_text:
Before the new week starts, we want to highlight our #OPSB spotlight of the week: Bryson Turner aka “Mr. President.” Bryson is an 8th-grade honor roll student at Alice Harte School.

Turner serves as the Student Body President and the band captain at his school. He was one the students who made a huge impression on our Chiefs for Change visitors last week.

When asked why did he want to become President of Student Government, he said quote: “I believe that I could be a voice for the students that didn’t have one.”

Although Turner plans to become a chemical engineer, we’re so excited to see what the future holds for him and hope he considers a run for President of the U.S. one day!

post_text: Come out and support our students as they rally and march for PEACE in the city of New Orleans. This student-led rally and march comes in response to the loss of 15-year-old Chance Smith and the gun violence that continues to plague the city of New Orleans. The March will begin at 10 am at the Superdome Gate A and will conclude in Duncan Plaza in front of New Orleans City Hall. This event is free and open to the public.
